{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 13:53:10.383625", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — multi‑tier Clos EBGP fabric\n\nSummary / overall health\n- Control plane (BGP) is healthy across the fabric: all expected eBGP sessions are UP on leaf, spine and super‑spine routers and the routers are exchanging prefixes. FRR BGP summaries show established sessions and prefixes being received (see evidence below).\n- I observed a single host‑reachability problem: the host pc_0_1 (10.0.1.2) is unreachable from its leaf (leaf_router_0_1) and other nodes. Other host subnets (for example 10.0.0.0/24 on pc_0_0) appear reachable from multiple locations.\n\nAnomalous behavior (what is wrong)\n- pc_0_1 (10.0.1.2) is not reachable; pings to it fail with \"Destination Host Unreachable\" from the leaf router.\n- The interface on the host pc_0_1 is administratively/down (state DOWN). This is the immediate cause of the lack of host reachability.\n\nLocalization (where the fault is)\n- Fault is localized to the host pc_0_1 (the endpoint), specifically its Ethernet interface eth0 appears to be down.\n- The leaf router connected to that host (leaf_router_0_1) is up and has the /24 network configured and being advertised via BGP — the problem is not in the router control plane or inter‑router connectivity.\n\nEvidence and relevant findings\n1) Host interface state (pc_0_1)\n- Output from pc_0_1:\n  - ip addr shows eth0 is present but in state DOWN and configured as 10.0.1.2/24.\n    - This indicates the host interface is not operational (no carrier / admin down).\n- Result: host will not respond to ARP or ICMP; leaf cannot forward packets to the host’s MAC.\n\n2) Ping from leaf_router_0_1 to pc_0_1\n- ping output: repeated \"From 10.0.1.1 icmp_seq=N Destination Host Unreachable\"\n  - This is the router’s local ICMP reply indicating it has no layer‑2 reachability to the host (no ARP entry / host unreachable on link).\n\n3) Leaf and network configuration (leaf_router_0_1)\n- leaf_router_0_1:\n  - eth4 = 10.0.1.1/24 (local host-facing interface) — interface is UP on the router.\n  - ip route shows 10.0.1.0/24 is local on eth4 (kernel route).\n  - eth4 RX/TX counters show essentially no RX from host (RX packets 0), small TX — consistent with peer not transmitting.\n  - FRR running config contains \"network 10.0.1.0/24\" and BGP neighbor statements — the leaf is advertising the host subnet and BGP is working.\n\n4) Control plane (BGP) and routing across fabric\n- FRR \"show ip bgp summary\" (parallel captures) indicates:\n  - leaf_router_0_0 and leaf_router_0_1 have their neighbors established and each is advertising its /24 (each leaf has its network configured in BGP).\n  - spine and super‑spine routers show neighbors up and prefixes present. RIB entries exist for the /24s and next‑hops point toward the appropriate leaves.\n- Example: leaf_router_0_1’s BGP summary shows its neighbors are established and it is advertising 10.0.1.0/24 (network statement present in running config).\n- Therefore inter‑router BGP routing is functioning; the route to 10.0.1.0/24 is present in the fabric and next‑hop is the leaf. The problem is not BGP/route distribution.\n\nOther observations (not strictly faults)\n- The BGP counters/messages look consistent with steady sessions; some neighbors show slightly different MsgRcvd counts (small differences) but sessions are established and stable in the observed outputs.\n- Reachability checks from many other hosts to 10.0.0.2 (pc_0_0) succeeded; reachability to 10.0.1.2 was unknown or failing — consistent with the single host failure.\n\nRoot cause (most likely)\n- The host pc_0_1’s NIC/interface is down (administrative or link down) causing it to be non‑responsive on 10.0.1.2. Because the host interface is down, the leaf router has no L2/ARP adjacency to reach the host, and therefore packets cannot be delivered even though routing and BGP are correct across the fabric.\n\nConcluding statement\n- Network fabric (EBGP, spine/super‑spine, inter‑router links) is functioning normally and the 10.0.1.0/24 prefix is advertised/known across routers. The single failure is at the endpoint pc_0_1: its eth0 is DOWN and that prevents host‑level reachability.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 19458, "output_tokens": 2153, "total_tokens": 21611, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 19200}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1088}}}
